Then, the sensitivity of this fluorescence ELISA in the detection of A. acidoterrestris was tested. As shown in Fig. 4
                        A, the fluorescence intensity of CDs at 510 nm decreases with the increase of A. acidoterrestris concentration from 0 to 106 CFU mL−1. When the bacterial concentration was in the range of 103 to 106 CFU mL−1, positive reaction was shown where the I/I0 was below the cut-off value. Moreover, a good linear relationship was obtained by plotting I/I0 versus the logarithm of A. acidoterrestris concentration in the range of 103 to 106 CFU mL−1 (Fig. 4B). The linear equation was Y = −0.1618X + 1.33509 with a coefficient of correlation of R2 = 0.9836 (Fig. 4B inset). Therefore, the LOD of this assay was calculated to be 6.16 × 102 CFU mL−1 with the cut-off value of 0.8837. The high sensitivity makes this proposed fluorescence approach perform better for the detection of A. acidoterrestris than the previously reported methods (Table 1
                        ). Generally, such relatively low LOD could be ascribed to two aspects. On the one hand, in comparison with the polyclonal antibodies, the high specificity of monoclonal antibody could reduce the nonspecific adsorption to nontarget microorganisms, leading to low background value. On the other hand, the CDs could sensitively respond to the quenching effect of PPDox, which is conducive to reduction of LOD. In addition, the deterioration phenomenon of fruit juice happens only when the concentration of A. acidoterrestris exceeds 105 CFU mL−1 (Witthuhn et al., 2012), which is significantly higher than the LOD. This means that the fluorescence ELISA could efficiently prevent the occurrence of spoilage caused by A. acidoterrestris.
